Meet big Midnight, a big dog, who's really a marshmellow inside. Midnight is fiercely loyal to his family and sweet a companion. He thinks he's a small lapdog and loves to snuggle with his human. He loves car rides and going anywhere he can be near his human.

Midnight is great with his female furry foster sisters and with the older children in the home. He would not be good with another territorial male or cats. Nor should he be in a home with small children just because of his size - he may get excited and accidently knock them down or step on them. Despite his large size, Midnight loves to play and has a lot of energy.

Midnight is housebroken and crate trained. He's very well behaved in the house and is not a trouble maker at all. His adoption fee is $125. For more information, please call 662-342-9448; email us via info@desotoanimalrescue.org or submit a pre-adoption application here: http://desotoanimalrescue.org/dog-adoption-application.html

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.

Handsome PRANCER is a 1.5 year old 55 lb. mixed breed boy looking for a furever home. He's a playful young dog who loves to fetch and chase squirrels. He also loves to cuddle and thinks 55 lbs. is the perfect size for a lapdog. Prancer has had basic training -- he knows shake, sit and stay. He looooves kids but needs a home that's on the quieter side because meeting new people makes him very anxious. He's fine with family activity, but not well suited to a home where lots of strangers are stopping by. Prancer would be happiest in a home with another dog who's confident and playful. He needs a physically fenced yard where he can fetch and fetch and fetch. Prancer is fully housebroken and crate trained. We aren't sure what his breed mix is, he's likely a mix of multiple breeds, but we believe he's part Labrador retriever, maybe some American Staffordshire terrier and who knows what else. If you'd like to meet this big handsome lovebug, please fill out a foster-to-adopt application at dreamhouserescue.org.

All of our fully-vetted adoptable dogs go to prospective homes for a one-week trial foster-to-adopt period to make sure the dog and home are the right fit before an adoption is finalized. We only adopt dogs into homes where all current pets are spayed/neutered and current on vaccines and heartworm and flea and tick prevention. We do check veterinary references to make sure adopters are compliant with standard veterinary care.
animal.name: Prancer

Hi, I'm Colin! The nice folks at RDR will update my profile when they learn more about me. I can't wait to share all the love I've got to give!

Adoption Application:

http://bit.ly/adoptrdr

Colin has tested positive for heartworms. Treatment will be paid for by RDR once they are adopted and settled in their home. Please note that this will require exercise restriction for 60 days and 2 visits to an RDR approved vet for treatment. For more information on heartworms click here:
https://www.heartwormsociety.org/pet-owner-resources/heartworm-basics

Adoption Application:
http://bit.ly/adoptrdr

Foster Application: http://bit.ly/fosterapprdr

Adoption Process: In order to adopt, we require an adoption application. After you submit an application, if you pass the screening, we will contact you to schedule a phone interview. We will call your references, including your veterinarian and landlord (when appropriate). We will also conduct a home visit. After these steps are complete, you will be approved to adopt a dog. Please note this process takes 1-2 weeks so applications submitted when you are ready to bring a dog home within that time frame. You can meet our adoptable dogs at events, however, we cannot guarantee that dogs at events do not have pre-approved applicants meeting them there as well, so the application is the best way to start the process.

Mission Statement: Forever true to "The Underdog", Rural Dog Rescue is dedicated to saving the lives of dogs in shelters who are often overlooked for adoption or rescue. We save the dogs who are at most risk of being euthanized: the hounds, the black dogs, the seniors, the sick and the broken. We make a commitment to reserve a minimum of 50% of the dogs we save to The Underdog. Root For The Underdog!

Rural Dog Rescue's home base is in Washington, DC. We adopt to the Washington, DC metropolitan area to include Maryland and Northern Virginia.

We support several high kill shelters that euthanize in 72 hours and whose kill rate is 70% or higher in rural areas of Virginia, West Virginia, North and South Carolina. Rural Dog Rescue also helps dogs in need in Washington, DC and Maryland.

We are 100% volunteer and foster based and no salaries are paid. 100% of your donation and adoption fee goes to helping the dogs and cats of Rural Dog Rescue.

Although we try to be as accurate as possible, Rural Dog Rescue cannot guarantee the breed or full-grown adult size of any of the dogs or puppies in its care. Because many of these dogs were found as strays or are the result of irresponsible, unplanned breeding, we do not know the dog's exact background and can only list breed and size by our best educated guess. If exact breed and size are important to you, please consider adopting a dog from a specific breed rescue. Our goal is for our dogs to be adopted by people who will love and care for them forever for who they are - no matter what breed and size they turn out to be!

All dogs go to their new homes spayed or neutered, up to date on all shots, dewormed (although a second deworming may be required), started on heartworm and flea and tick preventative and sometimes microchipped.

animal.description:
My name is Piper!
Im a 1 year old Terrier mix!
I am settling into my foster home well, I have 2 canine foster siblings that I love to play with. I’m a very happy girl with a lot love (& kisses) to give! I’m a very smart girl who has already mastered sit and I’m working on some more basic commands. While I was at the vet getting my shots and snips, I learned that I am heartworm positive. They told me no worries, the rescue will take care of me and I will be 100% healthy in just a few months. The best news is that I don't have to wait to be adopted - I can go home with my meds and just need a few more appointments at one of the rescue's partnered vets!
I love all people, I get along great with the smaller human in my foster home and I do awesome with other dogs! I’m working on going potty outside and I do well in my crate at night.

If you would like to learn more about or meet Piper, please fill out an adoption application on our website at k9s4u.org under adopt a pet, then contact Autumn @ 517-861-0619 once application is completed.
#K9s4uPiper

animal.description:
To be considered for adopting a dog from Canine Lifeline, you must have an approved application must be on file. Please visit http://www.caninelifeline.org/adoption-process/ for more information about our adoption process and to submit an online application.

If you love dog kisses, Kismet is your girl! This very friendly and affectionate 1 year-old Black Mouth Cur/Catahoula mix spayed female came to us as a stray from an overcrowded county dog shelter. When she wasn't claimed, she made the trip to Canine Lifeline so she could enjoy life in a foster home while searching for the perfect new home. While we don't have any history on her pre-shelter life, we have found Kismet to be a friend to everyone-human and canine alike. She even met the resident kitty at the vet clinic with a wagging tail and friendly demeanor but given that she's still very puppyish, she might chase kitties for fun. Kismet loves to play but can be a little mouthy when playing with her human friends. She would do well having a playful canine buddy in her new home to roughhouse with. Kismet is very food-motivated and seems to respond to the sit command so should be a quick study in obedience work. She has had excellent crate manners in her foster home and may be housetrained too although we can't guarantee it. Kismet gets very excited going for a walk so does pull some on the leash. She would do well with a harness as she works on her leash manners. If you're looking for an active and energetic canine buddy, Kismet would love to meet youu. Kismet weighs about 47 pounds and her adoption fee is $350. She's spayed, heartworm negative and on monthly preventative, up to date on vaccinations including bivalent canine influenza, wormed, on flea and tick preventative, and microchipped. As part of the adoption process, all adopters must commit to a two-week adjustment period to make sure it's a great match before the adoption is finalized. Please email info@caninelifeline.org if you're interested in Kismet. An approved application is required before we schedule meets with any of our dogs. Please note that we don't place our dogs in homes with children under 7 years of age. We correspond via email so please check your junkmail or spam folder to make sure our reply hasn't landed in there. Please visit our website at www.caninelifeline.org to see more photos of Kismet and to submit an online application if you live in Northeast OH.

JoJo: Estimated DOB: 1/13/2015, Chihuahua mix, male, 12.2 pounds, Good with dogs, Good with cats, No children
 
Sweet JoJo is looking for a very special adopter. He was rescued with several companions from a highly abusive situation. Your patience will pay off, because he is very sweet and loving to the ones he calls friends. He will jump into your lap and sit there until you want him to move. He is a low key dog that wants to be loved. He tries hard to please his person. If you have a true heart for rescue and lots of love to give then please choose sweet JoJo. He really needs a second chance!

JoJo will not be a good fit for a home with children.

Aeyoung’s a female jindo mix who is 3 years old ans weighs 25 pounds. She and Haru were among the 1,000 dogs rescued from the Aerinwon shelter after the Korean government shut it down for neglect and corruption. Despite losing her eye due to cataracts at a very young age, she is thriving with her foster family, and her spunky and sweet personality is developing more by the day! She’s getting straight A’s for her crate training, house breaking, and appetite.  While she can get spooked by the loud noises of NYC, she walks very well on her leash, and is a polite little lady with other canine (and human) passerby’s.  Has this one-eyed lady melted your heart yet? Apply to adopt Aeyoung!

———————------------------

Our adoption radius is now within 30 miles of the following locations:  NYC, Philadelphia, Lehigh Valley, DC, Baltimore, MD, and Western & Eastern CT. You must be able to pick up the dog at our office in Astoria, Queens (no exceptions). You must wear a mask and practice safe social distancing when traveling and picking up the dog.

INTERESTED IN ADOPTING?

NOT READY TO ADOPT BUT LOVE OUR DOGS?

animal.description:
Meet Prissy! This lovely 8 year old lab mix is a happy go lucky girl who will definitely melt your heart.

Prissy came to us from West Virginia after she was discarded for a younger dog. How awful

. But, that was Prissy's best day. This beautiful girl is fully housetrained, and there is no need to crate her because she is perfectly behaved when left alone. Prissy is UTD on all of her vaccines and is spayed and microchipped as well.

Prissy loves to follow her people so she can get all of the cuddles. She is wonderful with children (she absolutely adores her human foster sister) and is ok with another calm dog. Prissy is great on a leash and will take long walks with you or a nice jog. Prissy is not a huge fan of toys, and we think she just does not know what to do with them. A warm bed or spot on the sofa suits her just fine. Prissy does not know she is 8 years old, so she can keep up with an active family.

To be considered to adopt Prissy, please submit our Dog/Puppy Adoption Application as this is the FIRST step in our process:
https://form.jotform.com/203643479832159

NOTE: we are a foster-based rescue in Southeastern Pennsylvania which means we don't have a physical location (our sanctuary is for our farm animals only). We only set up meets for approved applicants and you must be located within 2 hours of Philadelphia.

animal.description:
Someone out there needs a total goofball in their life!    Meet Odie.   He is a ten month old deaf bully boy who loves eveyone and everything he meets.   He is all Goober and a lot of wiggle.   Odie gets along well with large and small dogs, and ideally would love a place where he could romp and play.   He is a happy smiley boy with energy and his happy shows with his tail wag.

At the time you are seeing this post, Odie is still available for adoption. But please know that we may be working on multiple applications already, and any one of them could be approved at any time. Please READ THIS ENTIRE DESCRIPTION and complete an adoption application, if you are interested in any of our animals. Application at www.greendogsunleashed.org   If you send an inquiry to ask if the dog is still available, or just tell us you are interested, your inquiry will not be answered. FILL OUT AN APPLICATION. We can do NOTHING without that. No, we cannot tell you if he would be a match for your family without seeing an application.  PLEASE KEEP READING for info.

*/*/* PLEASE NOTE:  The first communication you will receive after completing an application will be an email response, which will have instructions on how to proceed. Please check your inbox AND spam folders for the next 48 hours, for this email. We will not begin processing an application without the information requested in that email. */*/*

We are happy to consider applicants from out of state on most dogs. Please read the description to see if this dog is an exception.  If the applicant is approved to adopt, they MUST be willing to come to our location in Troy, VA, for a meet and greet. If all parties agree that the pup and family are a good fit,  they would take the pup home at that time.

For more information about our mission and for an APPLICATION for adoption, please go to www.greendogsunleashed.com.

GDU does ask a minimum adoption fee of $300.00. This does not even come close to covering all expenses created by animals while in rescue. We are funded solely by the angels and volunteers willing to donate time and finances. This minimum fee includes DAPP, rabies if age appropriate,, heartworm test and preventative, if age appropriate, and flea and tick treatment, as well as neutering or spaying, if the animal is medically sound to undergo surgery.  In an attempt to avoid tummy upset from a sudden change of food, the foster family may include a small, transitional bag of the food the dog/puppy has been eating. And if the dog/puppy has grown attached to a special item (like a toy or blanket), they may send that along, as well.

*/*/*  Young puppies will receive age-appropriate vaccines, and will be spayed/neutered prior to adoption. Adopters may be required to provide additional puppy boosters and at 16 weeks of age, a rabies vaccine. Future annual vaccines, testing and monthly heartworm preventative are REQUIRED, and will be the financial responsibility of the adopter.

He can be a little nervous when he goes to the doctor (who isn't!) so he would love if his new family helped him feel safer and more relaxed with some fun and positive training!

We are open to the public on a first come, first serve basis and are limiting our capacity to 50% in order to keep both our staff and community safe during this pandemic. HSP continues to provide an essential service to the community by intaking pets in need and finding adoptive homes. In order to continue operations, we must reduce the potential spread of the virus by taking extra precautions. We ask that all visitors entering HSP facilities wear appropriate face or mask coverings while maintaining at least a 6 foot social distance.

For more information on any of our Adoptable Pets, please visit our live website www.humanepinellas.org.  If you have questions on specific animals, please call 727-797-7722.  Our website is live so if an animal appears on the website, it is currently at the shelter.  However, the website does not reflect  adoptions in process or holds which have been placed for meet and greets on animals.  We suggest if you are coming to meet just one animal, please call first.

animal.description:
Saint Nick ACCT-A-21017
Intake: Owner Surrender
Sex: Male
Age: 6 years
Altered: No

**$50 in Pledges**

Medical Observations: 
12/22 (Intake Exam) -- Old wounds on all four legs healed; possible burn (healed) on front left ankle. 

Behavioral Observations: 
1/27 (Per Volunteer) -- Saint Nick is a ball of energy. But he's definitely a lover . 
When he sees me he knows he's going for a run and he's really happy . 
He's a big sprinter for about a minute but then settles into a nice 10 min a mile pace. 
I like to joke that he's a really good trainer as when he goes for a poop , he likes to go upside down against a tree like a human does against a wall upside down doing shoulder presses. 
He also trains my core really well because when he takes a potty break he really spins his back legs fast, kicking dirt, but he doesn't stop his legs spinning, then start running. He goes into his back leg spinning and then without stopping, starts his front legs so he's at tip top speed in less than a second, ( think the roadrunner) so I have to really hold my core really firm when he starts , every time he takes a potty break.
After that 5 sec burst of speed , he does slow down to a nice medium pace .
He really forms a strong bond with someone he's met a couple of times and is a really loving dog. 
Haven't tried any dog meets yet though. 
He definitely needs a home with an active person or a big yard, but he's a really really loving dog who makes my day when he sees me and knows he's about to run through the cemetery.
1/27 (Per Volunteer)-- He was calm in kennel and easy to leash. Once leashed and I opened the door to his kennel fully, he launched out like he was a race horse and pulled towards the door. He is VERY housetrained. He peed and pooped multiple times outside. When we got outside he saw another volunteer, who is his favorite running buddy. The other volunteer told me that Saint Nick is a star runner. We ran multiple laps in the parking lot. He is a great runner. Fast and straight, but we match pace and listen to cues for direction or slowdown. He checked in with me frequently. We then went into the big run. He enjoyed sniffs and would sit for treats. I had not attempted handling yet. He saw the other volunteer again through the fence and got very excited. It's clear he has an affection for him. He climbed up on the bench to get close to the other volunteer. After a few minutes he seemed to get very excitable and got the zoomies. He jumped up at me and launched back having put his front paws to my body. I decided it was best to end our time in the run, picked up his leash and we left the run. We did a few more laps in the parking lot and then proceeded to return to the building. On our way in he again spotted the other volunteer and stopped, waiting to see the other volunteer. So the other volunteer walked with us back into the building. He went into his kennel without issue
1/15 (Per Staff) -- Kennel Presentation: Easy to leash/social
Leash Skills: Pulls Strongly On Leash
Handleability: Aroused/Unable to handle - Currently not interested in being handled. Zooming around the yard. Frequently marking. Did jump on handler's lap and allowed some quick flank and head pats.
Tag: Aroused - Zoomies and will run into handler's legs.
Toys: No interest
1/8 (Per Staff) -- Kennel Presentation: Easy to leash/social
Leash Skills: Pulls Strongly On Leash
Handleability: Aroused/Allows some handling - Still shows no interest in actual handling but did come up several times and jump on handler's lap while in the yard. Allowed a pet on top of head when returned to kennel.
Tag: Aroused - Very excitable today and lots of zoomies
Toys: Interest but does not take possession - Interested in medium sized ball tossed. Chased, sniffed, and then ran right back to handler.
--uncomfortable with handling. Could use supervision of trainer and home environment.
1/3 (Per Staff) -- Kennel Presentation: Easy to leash/social - On bed on approach but gets up and comes to front of kennel when handler approaches. Easy to leash and remove from kennel. No issues returning to kennel and removing leash.
Leash Skills: Pulls Strongly On Leash
Handleability: Aroused/Allows some handling - Similar to previous eval. Will come when called and accepts short pets but tenses at touch and either curls body or flips his head toward handler. Did not push handling further.
Tag: No interest
Toys: Interest but does not take possession
12/26 (Per Staff) -- Kennel Presentation: Easy to leash/social
Leash Skills: Pulls Strongly On Leash
Handleability: Aroused/Allows all handling -- Allowed SOME handling. Came to get scritches/pets when called but would tense up slightly and curl into a "C" - immediately ceased and dog then relaxed. Was able to do this a few times throughout evaluation. Seemed extremely conflicted about touch, so did not push further.
Tag: Did not attempt
Toys: Interest but does not take possession
12/22 (Per Vet) -- Friendly; fearful; BAR
12/21 (Per Owner) -- LOVING; PROTECTIVE OVER ME AND HIS SPACE 

Bite Details: 12/26 (Per Email from Previous Owner) -- "Champ/ st. Nick was out the cage on the porch someone was trying to come in nick was trying to go out to attack and my daughter said "no champ move back" she just put her arm out so champ walk away and turned back around and bite her. He was trying to pretact her but the guy wasn't doing nothing for him to attack. Champ/nick just got mad cause she didn't let him attack.

Describe what happened during the bite. My daughter was bring in her girlfriend clothes in a bin so she was bring it in champ wanted to go out. "

From Bailey’s Foster mom:
“Are you looking for a calm, lovable blue heeler with perfect house manners? If so, please get your application in to Green Dogs Unleashed ASAP before Kevin B.  does!! I’ve already overheard him talking to Bailey....“go work your magic on your foster mom” ?
Bailey is 6 years old, deaf, neutered, house and crate trained and up to date on all vaccines. Loves car rides, belly rubs, Frisbees, tennis balls and hanging out on the couch in front of the TV. Is great with dogs of all sizes and cats. You will need to continue with his diet and exercise plan so he can get to his ideal weight :)”

At the time you are seeing this post, Bailey is still available for adoption. But please know that we may be working on multiple applications already, and any one of them could be approved at any time. Please READ THIS ENTIRE DESCRIPTION and complete an adoption application, if you are interested in any of our animals. Application at www.greendogsunleashed.org   If you send an inquiry to ask if the dog is still available, or just tell us you are interested, your inquiry will not be answered. FILL OUT AN APPLICATION. We can do NOTHING without that. No, we cannot tell you if he would be a match for your family without seeing an application.  PLEASE KEEP READING for info.

*/*/* PLEASE NOTE:  The first communication you will receive after completing an application will be an email response, which will have instructions on how to proceed. Please check your inbox AND spam folders for the next 48 hours, for this email. We will not begin processing an application without the information requested in that email. */*/*

We are happy to consider applicants from out of state on most dogs. Please read the description to see if this dog is an exception.  If the applicant is approved to adopt, they MUST be willing to come to our location in Troy, VA, for a meet and greet. If all parties agree that the pup and family are a good fit,  they would take the pup home at that time.

For more information about our mission and for an APPLICATION for adoption, please go to www.greendogsunleashed.com.

GDU does ask a minimum adoption fee of $300.00. This does not even come close to covering all expenses created by animals while in rescue. We are funded solely by the angels and volunteers willing to donate time and finances. This minimum fee includes DAPP, rabies if age appropriate,, heartworm test and preventative, if age appropriate, and flea and tick treatment, as well as neutering or spaying, if the animal is medically sound to undergo surgery.  In an attempt to avoid tummy upset from a sudden change of food, the foster family may include a small, transitional bag of the food the dog/puppy has been eating. And if the dog/puppy has grown attached to a special item (like a toy or blanket), they may send that along, as well.

*/*/*  Young puppies will receive age-appropriate vaccines, and will be spayed/neutered prior to adoption. Adopters may be required to provide additional puppy boosters and at 16 weeks of age, a rabies vaccine. Future annual vaccines, testing and monthly heartworm preventative are REQUIRED, and will be the financial responsibility of the adopter.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.All of the animals posted on our site have been temperament tested. While not all are in the immediate area, once we have processed and approved your application, we will move the dog to our adoptive area for you to meet, greet and hopefully adopt. Sometimes we will have more than one application on a dog. That does not mean it automatically goes to another family but you should be aware of the fact that until you are approved and set up for the meet/greet.. the dog could get adopted by another applicant.So sweet, so soft, with only one wish in the world...to be loved and cuddled, Bichon Buddy has waited all his life for a person to whom he can give his heart and little body. He hasn't given up. He is still hoping, after a lifetime of neglect. A safe, quiet, loving environment is what we are seeking for this small boy. Sadly, it's something he has never had. He's grown older, still imagining what it would be like to be cared for. He's started to get the creaks and problems that come to an aging dog, but still, he waits. Would you like to give this deserving boy this gift in his last years? Will you be his angel?Note from Buddy's foster: Buddy would love a home with another dog.
If you are interested in Bichon Buddy, please fill out an application at:
https://reachoutrescue.rescuegroups.org/forms/form?formid=4588 Or contact:
rorrcanine@gmail.com

animal.description:
Our Aptly named Summer reminds me a lot of the 90’s pop band LFO.   Happy tune, sweet sounding lyrics, but really all over the place and random....with little in the way of making coherent sense.  
Sure that isn’t a description that is going to sell this dog.   But the reality is this overgrown puppy is going to need an owner who doesn’t need to be sold on her.   She has had a really crappy first year of life.  Clearly she had never been on leash or in a house or ever EVER given any actual direction or stimulation in life.   She missed a LOT.   She missed how to play with toys, she missed how to play with dogs, and she missed how to expend energy outside of her chain and 3 foot circle.   Thankfully what she was given was clearly a naturally stunning disposition because this girl wants nothing more than to be touched and rubbed on.    Summer is going to need to learn EVERYTHING related to how to be an actual dog.   She is good with other dogs in the sense of existing next to them but will need to learn they can be fun playmates.   She needs to learn how to walk on leash.   We are working on this but right now she is a bullet out of gun and has no concept she should walk with you, rather than....”oh look there is a squ....hi are you New here?...oh I smell hotdogs!”  
Summer is currently a very high energy dog.  I am unsure if this is purely survival mode for her...expend all the energy you can at any given moment before you get chained again....or if it is just her.    What you see may very well be what you get.   As she is new here we will be continuing to evaluate this, though I suspect a home with a solid history of training and perhaps a job to do might be best.   She will find things to do and keep herself occupied but will need direction to not destroy your favorite metal food bowl.   Summer promises she gives the best snuggles.   For all the man handling I did to her myself today, she wanted nothing more than for me to touch her.   And touch her I did.   Ears, feet, tum, face...she melted into my legs and onto her back.   For as wild a child as this girl is, she is truly a lover at heart.   
We need a family with a LOT of patience.  This dog is NOT turnkey and will be a challenge.   A rewarding one for sure, but there will be frustration and hard work ahead.   Experience with a high drive dog is a must.   I have no idea how she is with cats.    
If you think you are up for a Challenge and can promise Summer the rest of forever, please fill out an application on our website.    For those of you just looking for a pretty Rotti face, enjoy her pics, but please understand this is not the dog for you.

animal.description:
Abileen is one of those dogs who is always happy, happy, happy! And she expresses her joy with lots of wiggles, kisses, jumping, and vocalizations. She's looking for a person who will love her as unconditionally as she will love them, and who wants to share their life with an adoring dog. There is no doubt this girl will keep you moving! She would love a place to live that has lots of safe space for her, preferably a fenced-in yard. As much as she would enjoy hiking or long walks, it's very stressful for her to see other dogs, and that's a very common occurrence on trails, so a life-style that doesn't involve those meetings would be best for her. Abileen LOVES to ride in the car, especially if you find yourself at a drive-thru!

Abileen has really improved with her impulse control, but she's easily excited, and still jumps a bit when greeting, so she would not be a good match for a family with small children. She was found as a stray with another dog, but now she says she only wants the company of humans. When Abileen has seen cats, she clearly wants to chase, so she should not live where cats are nearby.

Dogs: No

Cats: No

Kids: 13+

animal.description:
Please carefully read Joe's bio before applying
Unfit applicants won't be responded to

If you are interested in Joe, you can find our adoption process and the application on our webite;

straytoplay.org/adopt

Ideal home: Joe needs to be in a house (no condos or apartments) with a large backyard where he can hang out and do zoomies. He needs an active home, with someone that will take him for lots of long walks and hikes - 2 very long walks per day at the very least. He has a bit of separation anxiety, so a home where he has company throughout the day or has a canine sibling to keep him company. Joe needs people that can read his cues, as he does sometimes growl. So he needs a patient home that is willing to work on this.

Name: Joe

Age: approximately 5 years old

Breed: German Shepherd Mix

Weight: 62lbs

Gender: Male

Energy level: High. Joe needs a minimum of 10K walking distance per day. If he is not exercised enough he will pace around the home and not settle. He will sit at the door and paw at it. 

Good with dogs: If properly introduced to a dog he has been consistently good and enjoys their company. However, he will sometimes growl at dogs as they pass by on a walk. Still, he would do well with a canine sibling.

Good with cats: No. He has a high prey drive

Good with kids (+ ages): Joe should be in a home without kids.

Good with strangers: Joe was abused in the past, so he needs time to trust humans. He is not overly friendly with strangers, but mostly just ignores them. When introduced to new people, he needs a lot of time to warm up to them, and does not enjoy when new people are trying to touch him. 

Guarding issues: He will sometimes growl when on the coach, but does not guard food, toys, etc

Behavioural issues: He growls at people when they touch him/lean over him when he sits on the couch in the evening.

House trained: Yes

Crate trained: Joe has crate hate. He will paw at it the whole time. However, he is very calm and not destructive/not a chewer, so he is fine to be left alone with free roam of the house.

Separation anxiety: A little bit. He can been left alone for 2-3 hours.

Destructive: Not at all. 

Leash skills: Great. He is easy to walk and responds to commands. He is very smart and quickly learns what his humans’ want. However, he does lunge at squirrels. 

Okay with manipulations: Once he trusts you he will let you touch him and roll on his back for belly rubs. He lets strangers and new people pet his head. 

Medical issues: No

Other notes such as overall observations, personality, etc: Joe is a calm boy with an old soul. He is very curious, and wants to sniff and know what everything is before he relaxes. He loves being outside and exploring all of the smells. He enjoys being part of a pack - having another dog around gives him a bit more confidence on what is right and wrong, and when he can relax. At home, he is very friendly. He walks up and sticks his nose in front of you for pets and loves all the attention he can get. He is very treat motivated and eager to please, and will make any family happy.

We are unsure about cats at this time, but he does like to chase squirrels and rabbits and doesn't always listen to stop. Smokey also has not been around children. We don't anticipate any issues, but because of his size and energy level, a younger child may get knocked over. So we would like a home with older children only. Smokey does not guard anything and seems to be the all-around perfect mixer! He's hoping to find a family of his own to adore!

All pets adopted from GDHS are spayed or neutered, have vaccinations brought up to date, are on heartworm preventative (dogs), FIV/FELV tested (cats) and microchipped.
The Greater Derry Humane Society does not have a physical shelter, and all visits are by appointment only.

animal.description: Hello everypawdy! My name is Cami and you can recognize me by my big brown eyes. In fact, the only thing bigger than them is my heart! I am about 40 lbs. and a super joyful girl who loves the simple life. Being around my humans makes me super happy. The only thing that makes me happier is getting petted. It doesn't matter where, I'm not picky! I am pretty athletic, and if you want to go for a run, I am more than happy to keep up. I could be your perfect running buddy! Did I forget to mention that I get along famously with little dogs? My previous partner in crime is a Pomeranian and we did everything together, from playing tug of war to wrestling, no game is off limits to us. I can be super low profile if you need me to be, completely kennel trained and potty trained - I am a patient lady. So if you are looking for a patient, loving, energetic brown eyed girl, well I'm your girl. I would do best in a home with older children and a fenced yard to run around! If you are interested in meeting me please email foster.help@cityoffortwayne.org as I am still hanging out in a foster home. I looking forward to meeting you!

animal.description:
This is Decker, life has not been kind to him, and to add to his struggles this sweet boy got diagnosed with the dreadful "C word. 
He needs a hero...not one in a cape...just a normal one, with a warm home and a bed that he can spend his final time in. With the type of cancer he has it will be a few months. And in those few months we want him to know nothing but unconditional love and endless cheeseburgers. 
We can't control the amount of time we have with him but we can show him what kindness, love and a home is. 
Hospice fosters are truly special and to walk this journey will not be easy, but to Decker it will mean the world to him.

animal.description:
All interested people should submit an adoption application as their first step.
Sticks is an adorable chihuahua/greyhound mix who is about 8 years old. He is super affectionate with people and loves to snuggle. If you don't want a dog who likes to be on your bed or under the covers with you, then Sticks isn't your guy. This is his favorite thing ever! He much prefers to relax than be active. Sticks also loves to eat and will do a happy dance of circles when he sees his food come out! He is potty trained, but is working on not marking in the house so wears a belly band right now.
Sticks is curious about cats but just wants to be friends with them. He can be selective about other dogs and requires a proper introduction. Sticks loves his humans so can be territorial when it comes to other submissive dogs. He tends to not want to share but can do ok with commands and training. He has not been around children, but we are looking for a home without younger kids. He doesn't love loud noises and may nip if his things are taken while he is chewing them.
If you are looking for a loyal best friend to spend your days cuddling with, Sticks is waiting to hear from you!

All pets adopted from GDHS are spayed or neutered, have vaccinations brought up to date, are on heartworm preventative (dogs), FIV/FELV tested (cats) and microchipped.
The Greater Derry Humane Society does not have a physical shelter, and all visits are by appointment only.

animal.description:
Sissy is all puppy and very sweet! Lots of energy and needs boundaries, somebody to play with, and would do best in a home with another super playful and submissive dog/s. Because she is still puppy brained, sometimes her over excitement can be confused (by other dogs) as aggression. This is NOT the case but during introductions and the first few weeks or so, redirections may be needed so Sissy can learn about other dogs, their play style, and how to mesh in well with her new family. She responds very well to positive reinforcement. She has been around LOTS of dogs, big, small, males and females. Once she realizes her role and placement, she is the happiest go lucky girl you will EVER meet! We compare her temperment to a teenager:awkward and trying to find her place in the world.

Sissy does do well with kids, but because she's not always aware of her size, we suggest children in the home being 10 and older.

She is so super smart and would make an excellent hiking and running buddy! She absolutely LOVES activity in her life and needs to remain very active and keep her brain and body in motion.

She is about 45 pounds now but will be about 55 or so full grown. 

If you are interested in adopting, please visit our website and complete an adoption application at www.elpasocountycanine.org/available-dogs

animal.description:
Meet Barkley. Just shy of 6 months  old, this little guy (currently 38 pounds) is a ball of snuggly energy.  Loves playing with other dogs (especially chase me), going for long walks, eating (he can't get enough food!) and when he's finally worn out, he loves nothing more than to snuggle and cuddle with his people. 

Barkley is house trained and really good about not getting into things he shouldn't be, and if he starts to show some interest in something you'd rather he not have, he's happy to swap it out for a chew bone.

Barkley is learning to sit nicely (instead of jumping up) and to use his inside of voice (instead of barking).  He's a work in progress, but he's very smart and wants to please.  He's a very sweet boy.

Might he just be the perfect addition for your home?  

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ckqvTQOEd0g&feature=youtu.be

For more info on Barkley, check out his blog:

https://brooklinelabrescue.org/blog/barkley-black-labrador-retriever-mix-male-4-months-old-id-2834/



PLEASE NOTE:  While Barkley may not be available for adoption by the time you complete the adoption process, other great Labs are always finding their way into our Rescue. 

For more information on this Lab, please contact INFO@BROOKLINELABRESCUE.ORG.  

If you are interested in adopting this Lab or any other Lab from our Rescue, please visit our Web site, www.brooklinelabrescue.org, for more information on our adoption process. If you need additional information about the adoption process or whether you are in our coverage area, please send an e-mail to our Rescue at info@brooklinelabrescue.org

Even if you are not ready to adopt, you can still help us help our Labs!

Brookline Labrador Retriever Rescue is a 501(c)3 non-profit volunteer organization funded entirely by donations. Donations are always needed to help with veterinary costs, transportation, and supplies for our dogs. For information on donating to BLRR please click here. Donations are accepted via PayPal or you can mail a check to: Brookline Labrador Retriever Rescue, P.O. Box 638, Warrington, PA 18976-0638

He needs a furever home with a physically fenced yard to prevent him from going on walkabout again -- beagles are notorious for following their noses into trouble. T-Bone is about a year old and fully grown at 35 lbs. If you'd like to meet this good natured guy, please fill out a foster-to-adopt application at
dreamhouserescue.org.

All of our fully-vetted adoptable dogs go to prospective homes for a one-week trial foster-to-adopt period to make sure the dog and home are the right fit before an adoption is finalized. We only adopt dogs into homes where all current pets are spayed/neutered and current on vaccines and heartworm and flea and tick prevention. We do check veterinary references to make sure adopters are compliant with standard veterinary care.

animal.description:
Requirements: Thor would do best with adults & older children due to his activity level & high strength. 

 He should be the only dog in the household. 

 Due to his on-leash reactivity, Thor would do best in a home outside of the city away from dog congestion and with a fenced yard. 

Sex: Male 

Age: Young Adult- 2 years old 

Energy Level: Medium 

Strength Level: High 

Walks Best With: Freedom Harness
 
Intake Reason: Transferred in from another facility. 

More About Me: Hi, I'm Thor! I'm a very good boy and super playful. I am a growly player and love to play tug and fetch. When I've gotten all my zoomies out, then we can snuggle up on the couch together. I make the cutest little piggie grunts and I snore a little too -- sorry! I am a big boy and don't know my own strength so I might knock down younger kids. Sometimes when I see other dogs outside I might bark and pull very hard, but I'm working on my training! My friends in the Behavior department are so nice that they want to keep helping me be the best dog I can be even after I leave and find my forever home. I've been treated for some skin allergies while at the shelter and I'm feeling tons better [and my handsome self is finally coming through!] I'm on a medication called Apoquel long term to help prevent me from getting itchy but I take my pill like a champ. Are you looking for a side kick that'll turn heads and also make you laugh. Do you need a 60 pound lap dog? Then pick me, Thor! 

**Thor comes with FREE TRAINING! Included in your adoption fee, you will have access to Module One: Understanding your Reactive Dog. This is the first step to addressing your dog's on-leash behavior - understanding why they do what they do!** 

If you are interested in learning more about adopting this pet, click the [Adopt me] button to apply. 
Find a link to adopt this pet on our website: https://www.mdspca.org/humane-care/adopt/ 
 Primary Color: Tan Secondary Color: White Weight: 60.8lbs Age: 2yrs 11mths 1wks Animal has been Neutered

animal.description:
Porter is a very undersocialized 9 month old corgi / rat terrier puppy, who is still trying to figure out what it means to be a house dog. He was raised outside his whole life, and it's clear he didn't have much contact with people during that time. He has very specific needs, so please read his entire bio before applying.
Porter is a HUGE flight risk, which is similar to other dogs we've rescued from puppy mills. He will take any and every opportunity to bolt out the front door, and even will need leashed in a fenced yard for the foreseeable future. As such, we will NOT adopt him to anyone will small kids. This is non-negotiable, as we've had experience with kids letting dogs run out the front door and they've been lost or hit by cars. We try our best to set our dogs up for success, so please do not ask us to be flexible on this requirement. He will also need a secure, fenced yard that a 10 lbs puppy can't fit through.
Porter is not housebroken. He will need a patient owner, willing to deal with getting him through his puppy phase! We are also able to offer FREE training in the prison program to a new adopter, once the program reopens later this year.
Porter IS fully crate trained! His foster home has been a rockstar with this and it's paid off!
He also MUST HAVE a confident canine playmate, willing to show him the ropes! As you can see from his photos, he loves his Akita brother, and benefits greatly from following another dog and learning how to trust humans. He's shown no interest or aggression towards the cats in the home.
Porter has been neutered, vaccinated, microchipped, and is heartworm negative. His adoption fee is $350. If you are interested in Porter and meet all of his adoption requirements, please apply on our website, www.prodogsohio.org/adoptables.
He's being fostered in London, OH. Please note, we only schedule meet and greets with approved applicants. We are not currently hosting adoption events due to Covid.
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
We appreciate your support, in order to help us continue to rescue dogs! Donations can be made via our PayPal account - info@prodogsohio.org.
You must be willing to commute to the location that the pet is being fostered in order to be eligible to adopt. We do not ship our pets. We also require that you personally bring the pet back to us should the adoption not work out.
We do NOT negotiate adoption fees. All money goes to support our rescue operation. We are 100% volunteered based.
We require your current dog(s) to be current on vaccines and heartworm prevention.
Apply online at www.prodogsohio.org, under the Adoptables tab.
Due to the volume of apps and inquiries, we may not be able to respond to everyone.

animal.description:
Bonnie is very smart and sweet est. 4 year old Hu-Nose breed found as a stray.  She weighs about 45 lbs.  Photos do not do justice to her beautiful chocolate coat with varying shades of highlights.  She has had puppies sometime in her past but she is done with all that now ! She is a little fearful at first and with anything new.  However, she adapts very quickly and has been making great progress in learning trust.  If she feels cornered, she will let you know with a warning snap but I haven't seen this behavior since the beginning of her stay.  Otherwise if she is wary of you, she will avoid you.

She wants to be a very active girl and loves to run BIG zoomies in the yard.  She needs a family who can work with that energy and develop her full potential.  Even with this energy, she is pretty well behaved in the house and  does very well in a crate or ex-pen.   She has done quite well crated in the car for trips several hours long.

Bonnie will require a home with a fenced yard.  She needs room to run and due to her being prone to cautiousness of new people and situations, we do not want her to become a stray again !

Bonnie needs an experienced dog family.   We are working with trainers with Bonnie to overcome her fear issues with new people.   She is so super smart and learns very quickly but it is taking longer to learn about that trust with strangers.  She is making progress.  She knows SIT and will SIT, WAIT, LOOK when her food bowl is put down and then goes for it when given the signal !   Bonnie is looking for a family that has experience training dogs so she can continue her learning and a family that likes to be active, as she is very athletic !  She has been comfortable with men and women that she has learned to trust.   Bonnie's adoption would be a transition at this point to make sure she's comfortable with her new family and they are comfortable with her.  It would start with a series of brief meetings with Bonnie.

She has done ok with some dogs but not with others that try to intimidate her.  She should be in an only dog home or in controlled situations with other dogs to insure safety of all.

Bonnie Raitt was heartworm positive but has finished her treatments now.  She will be retested in March to confirm the heartworms are gone.

animal.description:
NAME:   DAX
GENDER: MALE
BREED:  FORMOSAN MOUNTAIN DOG MIX
COLOR:  BLACK & WHITE
AGE:     6 MONTHS OLD
WEIGHT:  33lbs
SPAY OR NEUTER:  Yes
MICROCHIP:  Yes

If you would like to give Dax a forever home, please go to 
www.adoptadoggie.org to fill out an online application with home photos.

Dax is a sweet and happy pup!  He is good with people, loves his humans, gentle with children, and good with dogs of all sizes.  Despite, living on the streets, he loves and trusts any humans he meets.  Dax has a good temperament and does not have a mean bone in him.  He is doing very well in his foster home and ready for his forever home.   Dax started some leash training and is learning at a good pace.  He is crate-trained and doing well on his housetraining.  He rides well in the car and can wait patiently while his foster mom runs errands.  Dax is a lovely boy and will make a good family dog.  Pls give Dax & Daxton a forever home together.  

DAX’s Rescue Story

Dax and his siblings were abandoned under a bridge with a pack of over 60 stray dogs.  They are living in horrible conditions and have no shelter and food.  The founder of a rescue organization got a rescue call.  The founder and her volunteers took 3 cars and drove down to the location.   A kind man who lives nearby and would often bring them some food.  He is the only person who cared for them.  People in the area were not nice and some would often beat them.  With the help of the kind man, the founder was able to catch all the puppies.  She cannot bear to see them suffer under the bridge.   Dax and his siblings arrived at the founder’s home at 1 am and they settled in nicely.  They were finally able to have a warm bed to sleep in.  She promised to find all of them homes so they can be treated with love and proper care.  

Dax had a thorough medical checkup.  He had been neutered, vaccinated, microchip, and passed negative on his blood tests.  Pls give Dax & Daxton a forever home together.

animal.description:
If you are interested in adopting this dog, please download and complete an Adoption Questionnaire from our website and email Debbie at debbied@k-9lifesavers.org
You can learn about the adoption process and find a Word, PDF and ONLINE version of the questionnaire by visiting: http://www.k-9lifesavers.org/howtoadopt/.
Dog's Name: Athena
Estimated Breed : St. Bernard mix
Approximate Age: 8-9 months
Approximate Weight: approx. 60 lbs
Currently Living at: Boarding
Adoption Fee: $300
DOG'S DESCRIPTION
Just look at that smile - this young lady just loves everyone! She would make an excellent family dog for a family that knows about large breeds. Athena is still growing and will need room to run and play. Athena is a super sweet and friendly girl who would make a great family dog. She is super sweet with people and gets along with other dogs. While she has her moments of energy, she can also be relatively laid-back and loves to give her humans "hugs". Will you give this big girl a loving family and home?
Your new pet will require a refresher in house-training. K-9 Lifesavers strongly recommends all new adopters enroll their new pet into obedience training. This provides for an easier transition into a new home, ensures the dog remains well socialized, and helps form a bond between the dog and the new family.
Adoption fees cover basic vetting, spay/neuter surgery (for dogs over 6 months old), rabies, distemper/parvo vaccinations, treatment for worms, heartworm testing, monthly heartworm prevention and monthly flea/tick prevention (while the animal is in our care), and transport costs from high-kill shelter. Please note that on average, K-9 Lifesavers spend significantly more on each dog than their adoption fee. Adoption fee for HW positive dog also covers heartworm treatment at our partner vets.
Foster Program: Foster homes provide for the temporary care of a rescue until the dog is placed into a loving, forever home. For more information on becoming a foster parent, and our Foster Program, visit http://www.k-9lifesavers.org/foster/ or email our Foster Coordinator at foster@k-9lifesavers.org
Sponsor Me! Make a tax-deductible donation today by visiting us at http://www.k-9lifesavers.org/donate/ . Donations help us offset boarding costs and additional medical treatment for those dogs who need it. K-9 Lifesavers receives NO federal funding and survive with your generous support!
For more information on K-9 Lifesavers, or to view a complete listing of all our Adoptable Dogs, visit our website at www.k-9lifesavers.org.
Please "like" our Facebook Page for the most current events and new dogs.
Thank you for considering a rescue dog!

GENDER: FEMALE
BREED:  FORMOSAN MOUNTAIN DOG MIX
COLOR:  BLACK

SPAY OR NEUTER:  Yes
MICROCHIP:  Yes

If you would like to give Brussels a forever home, please go to 
www.adoptadoggie.org to fill out an online application with home photos.

Brussels is a sweet and gentle girl!  She has been through a rough start in life and is shy with new people.  Once she settles down in a home, you will see her sweet and loving side.  Brussels loves her humans, gentle with children, and good with dogs of all sizes.  Brussels is doing very well in her foster home and ready for her forever home.   Brussels started some leash training and is learning at a good pace.  She is crate-trained and doing well on her housetraining.  She rides well in the car and can wait patiently while her foster mom runs errands.  We are looking for a committed home to continue to socialize/train her and be patient with her during the transition period.  

BRUSSELS’s Rescue Story

Brussels and her daughter, Brighton, were abandoned under a bridge with a pack of over 60 stray dogs.  They are living in horrible conditions and have no shelter and food.  The founder of a rescue organization got a rescue call.  The founder and her volunteers took 3 cars and drove down to the location.  A kind man who lives nearby and would often bring them some food.  He is the only person who cared for them.  People in the area were not nice and some would often beat them.  With the help of the kind man, the founder was able to catch 28 of them.  She cannot bear to see them suffer under the bridge.   Brussels and her buddies arrived at the founder’s home at 1 am and they settled in nicely.  They were finally able to have a warm bed to sleep in.  She promised to find all of them homes so they can be treated with love and proper care.  

Brussels had a thorough medical checkup.  She had been spayed, vaccinated, microchip, and passed negative on her blood tests.  Please give Brussels a loving home where she will never be left behind again.

Stop thief!! … is what you may often find yourself saying if you’re lucky enough to live with Cricket, who fancies herself to be The Great Hoarder Of Socks (and shoes, stuffed animals…you get the idea). 

Still a puppy at just a year old, she is sweet as can be and sure to keep you laughing with her antics.

She has three great loves — eating (stealing food), playing (stealing toys), and cuddling (stealing hearts!) 

Cricket’s gentle, loving nature would match very nicely with older, dog-savvy children (10+). Everyone in the home should enjoy getting kisses – they’re good luck! A true family dog, she will be happiest in a home with multiple humans to dote on her.

Cricket is initially timid with new people, but warms up very quickly. 

A SECURE PHYSICAL FENCE WILL BE REQUIRED TO ADOPT HER.  

She loves to play with other dogs and would do well with a more confident, similarly aged canine companion, but we think she could be happy as an only dog as well. 

She is not suited for a home with cats or small animals as she is too interested in playing with them. Cricket is housebroken, but gets nervous when left for long periods so her adopters should have a flexible schedule.

If you’ve been longing for a cuddly, playful sock thief in your life, Cricket is your girl!

animal.description:
Meet Priscilla, AKA Miss Prisc! The inspiration for her name was a male, so we chose to name her after his wife. She is an approximately 3-year-old Rat Terrier mix who came into our program for bad behavior at a local shelter. She spent approximately eight months in a spacious home, hiding under furniture, avoiding human interaction, mostly refusing love, and scared of collars and leashes. The freedom to adjust in her own time only allowed her to become more scared of humans and more reclusive. ? In December, we changed tactics and moved her to an active socialization fostering situation, and we are so glad we did!! In one month, she went from being so scared of humans she would fear bite to begging for her foster mom's attention and sleeping in her lap every chance she gets. She still has a ways to go. She's very timid with anyone new, but more timid with men. She takes treats from her foster mom and foster dad's hands. She no longer tries to bite anyone that reaches into her playpen to pet her or tries to pick her up. She no longer rolls or flails around to get away from a collar / halter and leash. She's still a bit scared of actually walking on a leash, but she is slowly figuring out that it isn't torture! ?

This sassy girl has attitude for days, but it is mostly rooted in her fear of human interactions. She will do amazing in a single human or one couple home (we are not sure a home with kids would be good for her), and would likely really prefer a woman to be her person. Once she feels comfortable and safe, though, she will be the sweetest love bug!

She will need a human who is willing to spend some time in the beggining helping her understand they are not a threat. She is very unlikely to immediately bond with any potential adopter / family. We anticipate her regressing slightly when she finds her forever home, just due to the severity of her fear of humans and fear of new things in general. She will do best staying in a large, enclosed playpen or kennel that opens from the top in the first couple to several weeks until she adjusts. That way her human can place a blanket over her to help her feel secure before picking her up. She LOVES soft fleece-like blankets. They are her very favorite place to curl up and nap! She is very fast when she gets scared and wants to get away, and will be hard to catch if she hasn't adjusted to the human trying to catch her. If she is let loose in the home, it may be a much harder and longer process to earn her trust. This is exemplified by the difference in how much progress she has made in a more controlled setting in such a short time compared to the little to no progress she previously made with too much freedom in the beggining. ?

Priscilla is mostly potty pad trained, but she misses the pads occasionally and goes beside them. She is not kennel or house trained, but she is working on it! We do not expect this to take long once she feels a bit more comfortable on a leash / loose in the yard or her foster family is able to get an outdoor enclosure to use for her potty breaks (their yard is huge and they don't want her to get scared and find a hole in the fence or get hurt in a panicked state). Her fear of basically everything was our higher priority, but her foster mom is focusing on training more now that she feels safe!

Priscilla might do best as an only pet, but we would be happy to consider a family with other small dogs or cats. She has been very reactive with large dogs (male and female) in our experience, but might be okay with a small to medium dog. She gets along with female cats, but does not appreciate male cats in her personal space.

She is spayed, micro-chipped, up to date on age appropriate shots, heartworm negative, and on flea, tick, and heartworm prevention!! She will be available for adoption in the next few weeks, but we are taking applications now. Www.muttmisfits.com/adoption-application

From the Foster Family: Uso is a very friendly and loving dog who is looking for a family to call his own. He loves to play, whether it's a good game of fetch, running around in our fenced-in yard with another dog, or playing with some dog toys. He loves chewing on bones and toys and is great at "de-stuffing" the soft ones. He's been really good about knowing what's ok to chew on though and has not chewed on anything that he shouldn't. He typically likes to be close to his people and will come to sit with you on the couch for a little snuggle time, a belly rub, and even a few kisses!

He has learned how to sit and is getting pretty good at stay too. He is very motivated by treats and will work hard to earn them which is good because he is going to need some work with learning how to walk on a leash as he tends to pull quite a bit. In light of that, he would do great in a home with a fenced-in yard so he can get some exercise while being off-leash. At night, he's been sleeping in a crate and has done well with that, settling down quickly and sleeping quietly through the night. I'm sure he'd love to sleep in a dog bed, on a nice comfy couch, or on your bed too! Uso would make a great watchdog as he typically barks when he hears the door open. No one will sneak up on you when he's around! If you're looking for a fun, friendly, and loving addition to your family

, Uso could be the guy for you!

animal.description: Welcome Teddy to Lucky Dog Rescue. Teddy is a 11-12 month old Springer Spaniel weighing about 35lbs. Teddy is part of the China Rescue Dogs mission to save as many dogs as possible from the meat festival that coincides with Chinese New Year. We know Teddy was likely someone’s pet that was discarded in March or April after the start of COVID when it was wrongly believed that pets carried the virus. Not true! It was somewhere around this time he was rescued and placed in a foster home. For months Teddy has been in a boarding facility getting up to date on his vaccinations ,neuter ,quarantine, passport and then finally his flight to New York USA! Teddy will arrive in the US on February 5th after nearly 35hrs of travel and then Lucky Dog will pick them up with the others on February 6th .During this time adopters will receive updates on their dogs and have access to the group chat and message group. On February 6th they will be available for meet and greets and to potentially head to their forever homes! Teddy is the happiest and sweetest boy! He loves everyone he meets. He does well with other dogs and surprisingly doesn’t have an resource guarding issues!! Teddy being a young hunting breed dog has lots of energy and we suggest anyone considering adoption research the breed first. Teddy  is crate trained however he may not be receptive the crate after arrival. He will need help to reestablish housetraining after travel and being in a boarding facility. He is in perfect health and is fully up to date on all of his vaccinations, tests, and neuter. He will be microchipped and will be registered to Lucky Dog Rescue for the rest of his life. After Teddy has settled in at his forever home we will need to schedule him at one of our partner vet locations for his “cherry eye” repair surgery. The surgery will be covered by the rescue at one of our partner vet locations. It is a minimally invasive surgery to remove the second eyelid that has not grown in well. There won’t be any issues long term for his Vision. Teddy’s adoption fee will not be inexpensive. Due to border closures and needing to fly cargo, his flight alone without medical care is $750 for a dog his size. We are asking $950 minimally but appreciate anything beyond that to help other China dogs. Half of the $950 will need to be paid after the phone interview to hold him until February 6th. If the adoption isn’t successful at time of meeting his deposit is returned. Teddy’s entire fee will be going back to Chinarescuedogs.org to help get other dogs to freedom in the US. With all of our adoptions if at any point the adoption isn’t successful within the first two weeks the entire adoption fee is returned. After the two weeks of the dogs need to be rehomed for any reason the dogs must be returned to the rescue.

animal.description:
Teller is scheduled to arrive at the farm in early Feb. He comes to us from MS where he was a stray that keep showing up in people's yards then disappearing only to reappear in another.  This earned him the name Teller as in Penn & Teller, the magicians.  This is also typical behavior of a great pyr left off leash in an unfenced yard, they know no boundaries! 
Lucky for Teller the nice folks at Union County Humane were finally able to catch him and he has been in foster care while getting him vaccinated, neutered and ready for his big trip north.
We believe Teller is just under a year old.  He is on the smaller side about 70 pounds so may still have a bit of growing to do.  He is very sweet and doing well learning to walk on a leash and crate training and not being a wandering man.

If you are interested in this dog please fill out an online application on our website:                          https://.barkdogfarm.rescuegroups.org/forms/ 

Before applying be sure you have thoroughly researched Great Pyrenees.  They can be stubborn, prone to barking, overly protective and cannot be off leash.  You WILL NOT train a pyr to boundaries.  
Please be sure all family members are in agreement to adopting and your family is ready to bring dog home now. 
Applicants must be at least 21 years old. 
A volunteer will be in touch to discuss your application and the dog to determine if it is a good match. Your vet and two references will be called.  A virtual home visit done. Once approved a meet and greet at the farm will take place.  If all are in agreement and the animal has received its NH health certificate an adoption contract will be signed and adoption fee paid.  
Adoption fees for dogs are $450. for adults over 12 months, $500 for puppies 12 months and younger.  Fees for seniors, special needs or harder to place dogs will be determined by our Board of Directors.
 All dogs will be altered when adoption is finalized, up to date on age appropriate core vaccines, negative for parasites, heart worm and lyme tested if 6 months or older, microchipped and have a current health certificate.  
Proof of a basic obedience course completed is part of our adoption contract within six months. 
Our descriptions are based on shelter evaluations, input from foster homes and interactions with our volunteers therefore are in no way a guarantee of temperament. 

! Please know we practice Covid-19 guidelines for mask wearing and social distancing.  Only approved applicants are allowed to meet our dogs outdoors at this time. Please email barkingdogfrm@gmail.com with any questions.
animal.name: Teller-coming soon

******If you are interested in learning more about this puppy, please complete an application by visiting http://www.floridaurgentrescue.com/adopt.********

Meet Boomer!  What do you see  first when you look at Boomer??? You see a BIG SMILE as he is one happy, happy, joy, joy dog!!!  Boomer was found as a stray in Lake Butler, FL.  Despite it all, this boy just loves life. and you can't help but smile when you see him.  Boomer is heart worm negative (yay!), in good health but may need to loose just a little weight which is easily obtained by giving him exercise. He is great with other dogs and most likely will be fine with children over the age of eight. As often the case with shelter dogs, Boomer tends to guard his food and one will need to work with him on his resource guarding.  He also does not like loud noises such as sirens.

Boomer weighs 55 lbs but thinks he is a lap dog. He walks well on a leash and we think he is about 2-3 years old. He is neutered, has his vaccines and is ready to go to his forever home.

***Please note that we are a volunteer run organization, and due to the large volume of applications, inquiries, phone calls, emails, and messages received we may not be able to provide a detailed, personal response to every single one. For that reason, formal applications will be given priority over the aforementioned.***

Adoption Process
1. Submit Application
2. Interview
3. Home Check
4. Meet the Pet

The adoption fee for puppies 6 months and under is $225; this includes the spay/neuter, rabies, microchip, and current vaccinations as of the date of adoption.

animal.description: Gertie is a very special girl to us. She had apparently been wandering on her own in the woods for some time. A good Samaritan brought her to Haywood Emergency Clinic where she was found to be malnourished and suffering from severe ear infections and parasites. A search for an owner got no results and she was transferred to Sarge's. After lots of treatment and TLC, she was able to have her spay surgery. We think she's 8+ years old, so a senior, but that doesn't slow her down! She's an awesome, sweet dog whose tail is always wagging, and she loves her people, especially if there are treats involved. She never messes in her kennel. She is now available for adoption! If you'd like to meet her, please complete the application online at www.sarges.org and we'll be contacting folks to set up appointments.

Hi, my name is Shiitake! I'm estimated to be a Mastiff mix born 9/25/2020. I came up to Wisconsin from Texas. I am a happy and playful little girl! Obedience classes for adult dogs and puppies can be incredibly helpful for both animals and humans. It helps you understand what makes me tick and will give me a better idea of what you want me to do. It’s a win/win and it will also strengthen the bond between us! Apply for me today!

My adoption fee is $350.00. Adoption applications can be filled out at CCHS or online through our website, www.cchs-petshelter.org. Applications are not first come, first served. All applications will be reviewed by the adoption committee and the home chosen will be the one considered to be the best match. All dogs and puppies have been vaccinated for Distemper and Bordetella, dewormed and microchipped. If old enough, they will be vaccinated for Rabies and blood tested for Heartworm, Lymes, Anaplasmosis and Erlichiosis. Dogs and puppies will be spayed or neutered before adoption.

CCHS is proud to be a No-Kill Humane Society. As a private, non-profit charity, our work depends on donations and volunteers to keep going. We are committed to helping the animals that enter our doors and finding each the best possible forever home. CCHS has been inspected and licensed by the Department of Animal Health - DATCP. Our license is #268235-DS

Phoenix's adoption fee is $225.00 which includes 3 rounds of shots, spay, microchip and 1 month of heartworm preventative. If you are interested, please complete the

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Our sweet little Ice Cream puppies are ready for their new homes! This litter came to us after their mama got hit by a car :-( they needed to be kept safe! They are little chihuahua mixes, just over 3 months old.

The puppies are full of life! There is never a dull moment with 6 puppies running around! They are very playful, sometimes rough but always ready for cuddles with their foster family. They live with other dogs of various sizes in their foster home and do well with everyone. They like the house cats too! Although they have not been exposed to kids while in rescue, we do not believe there will be an issue as long as the kids are kind and respectful of their small statures. Housetraining is still a skill in need of work - right now they use pee pads. One or two will venture outside into the snow but then quickly hightail it back inside! They love toys and chewies are a favorite. They are gated or penned at night and when their foster family is gone for the day. They still need training and that

Rocky is another little boy looking to get into trouble any way possible! He loves to start trouble with the older dogs in his foster home and when corrected, runs crying to his foster mom! She knows his game now. He loves to play with his siblings and loves to steal toys. If you feel something nibbling on your toes - it's Rocky! He just wants to be loved - how can you say no to him?

Rocky is scheduled to be vetted on Feb 2 but we are accepting applications now. He will be neutered, up to date on age appropriate vaccines, microchipped, flea/worm treated at the time. His adoption fee is $400

animal.description:
We  are helping Abby find a new home. Her  owner  had her as a  puppy  but  has  to  move  and will  be in an  apartment with a pet weight limit.
 
Abby  is a 22 month old female  GSD.  She is happy  and affectionate,  around  her  family,  but  takes time to  warm up to  new  people  and  dogs.  An  owner with  some  GSD  experience who  can  work on  her  shyness and  socialization  would  be  best  fit. She's  up to date on vaccines and is spayed. 

Abby is  friendly  to  people and  does  well  living in a  home.  Because  of  her  shyness, a home  without small  kids is  best  for  her. .She's  young,  and   an active  home  would   work  well. 

 Abby  is living  with  another  dog,  and  has  done well,  and  has  been  fine with  dogs  in training  class when  properly  introduced.  A  dog  her own  size  and  age  would  be a good  fit,  and  she  could  do  well as  the only  dog.  She  is  not  good  with  cats or  smaller  dogs. 

She is housebroken, leash  trained, and  knows  basic  commands. She  has  been  through basic training.

To meet Abby,  please contact ryukenblue@aol.com directly, and let  them  know  you  are interested to  meet her.

animal.description:
Hello, meet cute Chica. She is an honorary Great Pyrenees, disguised as a three-year-old, eleven pound, Chihuahua mix. She was rescued by the Great Pyrenees Rescue Society from a Texas animal shelter.

Chica is a sweet, friendly girl who gets along with everyone she meets. She likes to burrow under blankets and snuggle with you. Nothing makes her happier than being close to you. She is house and crate trained.

Chica will thrive in an adult only home. She needs a family who will treasure her the rest of her life. Please complete an Adoption Application. She is only available for adoption in OR and WA.

All dogs and puppies require VISIBLE fencing

Adoption Fee:
$450
. (Adoption fee includes spay/neuter, heartworm test, rabies, distemper, parvo and health certificate for travel). Northwest adopters pay the cost of transport to independent transport service ($225). Adoption applications can be found on our website at https://www.greatpyreneesrescuesociety.org/.

ADOPTION, FOSTERING, AND DONATIONS are just some of the ways you can help a rescued dog. We have worked hard to cultivate a large network of volunteers to save this majestic breed. While monetary donations are always much appreciated, you can also help by donating your time as a GPRS foster or volunteer!

animal.description:
So often the first thing we see are the eyes. The sad, terrified eyes looking out at a world that has repeatedly betrayed them. Jester’s eyes tell us a story we already know. Pain. Fear. Inhumanity. It’s a story we can’t, we don’t want to unsee. Whether large or small, these dogs’ eyes beg us for what they’ve never before had — love, compassion, understanding, and respect. Jester doesn’t know why he was in the shelter. He had a family once, but no more. Shelter life for this handsome lad only added insult to injury. The chaos, the instability, the constant new faces...it was all just too much for Jester. As a result, he did the only thing he knew to survive. He growled, showed his teeth, and never quite allowed himself to trust anyone. There were some with whom he occasionally engaged, but almost always with trepidation. It was clear they needed to find a rescue, and we were more than happy to bring Jester into the Perfect Pet Rescue family. He weighs 18 pounds and is neutered, microchipped, and current on his vaccines. We are now working with Jester and hope to find a home with an experienced dog owner who will join him on his journey and promise to support and guide him as he heals.

To see our other dogs, please visit www.perfectpetrescue.com.

animal.description:
Vienna is a 10 week old, female lab mix who weighs about 12 pounds and has a short, shiny black coat with some white markings on her nose, chin, tummy and paws.  We expect she will be 50-65 lbs when fully grown. Vienna is a delightful, playful, smart dog!  She very quickly adapted to her foster home, sleeps through the night and enjoys napping in between play sessions.  She is crate trained and loves to play with children and run around outside (although the current cold temperatures require a little cajoling to get outdoors).  She is learning to play fetch and basic commands (sit and come).  A typical puppy, she loves to chew anything she can get her mouth on.  She is quickly learning to toilet outdoors but is also trained to use wee-pads inside.

Vienna has a happy, laid-back personality and would be happy in a house with kids and/or other dogs.  A fenced-in yard or family that will take her on frequent walks would be ideal.

animal.description:
Dublin is an absolutely delightful 10 week old, 13 pound lab mix puppy, who we expect to be about 55-65 pounds when fully grown. While this little guy initially approaches new people and situations cautiously, his curiosity soon gets the better of him, and he will enthusiastically join in on all the fun.  Dublin is a sweet natured and playful puppy who loves his toys and balls and has become quite accomplished at fetch. He is doing well with crate and potty training, and if he can't make it outside in time, he will find the nearest wee wee pad to do his business. 

Dublin's foster family tells us that he is happiest when he is with his people. He is eager to go out and learn about the world and is always up for an adventure, whether it be a ride in the car or a nice long walk on his leash. Dublin is full of silly puppy energy, but once play time is done he is very happy to snuggle on the couch with you for a good belly rub and a nap. He is a people pleaser and highly motivated to learn good manners and appropriate behaviors. Affectionate and loving, Dublin is a handsome dog who will always bring a smile to your face.

animal.description:
Spunky Sadie is a 2 year old, 40 pound Beagle/Hound mix, who is sweet as sugar! Sadie is super friendly and wants to be everyone's best buddy.  She loves getting out on long walks and meeting new people and other dogs, and is working very hard on her leash skills. She is also learning to enjoy car rides as she now understands that there will be something fun to do at the end of the trip. 

Sadie is house trained and well behaved in the home. Alert and curious, she always wants to know what goodies and new adventures are hidden behind a gate or just out of reach on a counter. She is playful and enjoys her toys, but doesn't show any interest in fetching sticks. Sadie is not fond of her crate and much prefers a nice soft dog bed near her people. Her appetite is good and she is currently eating three meals a day in her foster home to gain some much needed weight. Sadie would do well in a home with a fenced in yard where she would be able to safely explore her surroundings. She is great with other dogs and children, although she is very strong and may be better with older children who can understand and encourage her enthusiastic nature. Sadie will be a wonderful addition to an active family - could it be yours?
